description:
## Why

User-supplied display names (set via /iam and group_create) are stored and broadcast to all connected users without normalization. This creates spoofing attack vectors:

- RTL override: U+202E RIGHT-TO-LEFT OVERRIDE renders 'groupname' as 'emanpuorg'
- Homoglyph spoofing: 'niе' using Cyrillic е (U+0435) is visually indistinguishable from Latin 'nie'
- Zero-width characters: two names with different bytes can appear visually identical

An attacker can create a group or nickname that appears to be a trusted identity.

## What

Apply canonicalization in `ws.rs` set_nickname handler and `store.rs` group_create before any storage or broadcast:

```rust
use unicode_normalization::UnicodeNormalization;

fn canonicalize_display_name(s: &str) -> Result<String, &'static str> {
    let s: String = s.nfc().collect();  // NFC: prevents homoglyph bypass
    let bidi: &[char] = &[
        '\u{202A}', '\u{202B}', '\u{202C}', '\u{202D}', '\u{202E}',
        '\u{2066}', '\u{2067}', '\u{2068}', '\u{2069}',
        '\u{200E}', '\u{200F}',
    ];
    let zwsp: &[char] = &['\u{200B}', '\u{200C}', '\u{2060}'];
    let s: String = s.chars()
        .filter(|c| !bidi.contains(c) && !zwsp.contains(c))
        .collect();
    let s = s.trim().to_string();
    if s.is_empty() { return Err("empty after canonicalization"); }
    if s.chars().count() > 32 { return Err("too long"); }
    Ok(s)
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria

- set_nickname with RTL override chars returns an error
- set_nickname with zero-width chars strips them silently
- group_create with homoglyph name is NFC-normalized before storage
- Names over 32 chars (post-canonicalization) are rejected
- Unit tests cover: clean name passes, RTL rejected, ZWS stripped, homoglyph normalized, 33-char rejected
- DESIGN.md §Display Name Canonicalization documents this as a security invariant
- unicode-normalization added to nie-relay Cargo.toml if not already present
